EQUINE HERPESVIRUS- USA (MICHIGAN)(04)
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 23 Dec 2004
From: Michael J Studdert <m.studdert@unimelb.EDU.AU>

Dr Luce provides an accurate and brief description of EHV1 and EHV4
nomenclature and some preferred common names for the diseases these 2
viruses cause. The fact that both viruses cause acute and recurrent
respiratory disease that is commonly referred to as rhinopneumonitis means
that, without laboratory confirmation, terminology for the viruses may
continue to be ambiguous.
In the last sentence of his posting Dr Luce states "Importantly,
vaccination does not offer protection against neurological manifestations
of disease." It may be more correct to say that we do not know whether
vaccination may have a protective role in preventing EHV1 myeloencephalitis.
As in the case of abortion, EHV1 vaccination may not be expected to provide
100 percent protection against EHV1 myeloencephalitis. An earlier posting
(Archive Number 20031110.2785) and a published paper (1) described a major
outbreak of EHV1 myeloencephalitis in which it was shown that in a group of
10 mares, 5 mares that did not develop myeloencephalitis were EHV1
antibody-positive, while of the 5 mares that did develop myeloencephalitis,
3 that were tested were either EHV1 antibody negative or had a rising EHV1
antibody titre.
The results of this study provide the first clue that specific EHV1
antibody negativity is a major risk factor in the development of
myeloencephalitis and that -- accordingly, by analogy with a reduced
incidence of abortion -- vaccination could reduce the incidence of
myeloencephalitis in horses at risk.
Reference
1. Studdert MJ, Hartley CA, Dynon K, Sandy JR, Slocombe RF, Charles JA,
Milne ME, Clarke AF, El-Hage C (2003) Outbreak of equine herpesvirus type 1
myeloencephalitis: new insights from virus identification by PCR and the
application of an EHV-1-specific antibody detection ELISA. Vet Rec 153: 417-423
--
Michael J. Studdert
Professor, Veterinary Virology
School of Veterinary Science
The University of Melbourne
Parkville, Victoria 3010
Australia
<m.studdert@unimelb.edu.au>
