Date: 23 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Standardbred Canada website [edited]
<http://www.standardbredcanada.ca/news/iss1204/equineherpes1222.html>

2nd Horse Has Equine Herpes Virus
-------------------------------------
A second horse at Northville Downs in Michigan has tested positive for the
equine herpes virus 1 (EHV-1).
The Michigan Department of Agriculture erected a quarantine barn at
Northville Downs after a test from 8 Dec 2004 confirmed one horse had
contracted the virus.
The 1st horse to test positive was Speedy Tino, a 6-year-old gelding son of
Survivor Gold that had been claimed from Hippodrome Trois Rivieres by
American interests. The horse has since been humanely destroyed.
Animal health surveillance detected a 2nd horse that was under quarantine,
showing symptoms of the virus and tests performed on 20 Dec 2004 confirmed
the horse had contracted EHV-1.
The equine herpesvirus can cause respiratory infection, abortion or
neurological disease in horses, and can be fatal. Although humans and other
animals are not at risk of contracting the virus, it is very contagious
amongst horses.
Other indications that a horse may have contracted the virus include fever,
cough, runny nose or neurological signs, and symptoms generally appear
within 21 days of exposure.
Horse owners with questions are encouraged to contact the Michigan
Department of Agriculture state veterinarian office at (517) 373-1077 or
the Office of Racing Commissioner at (734) 462-2400.
